{
  "text": "We used two features extracted from gene-expression patterns, namely expression level 'continuity' and 'variance', originally proposed by G\u00fcell et al. [CITATION_1] and Toledo-Arana et al. [CITATION_2] , both of which used a similar variance feature to detect TUs from RNA expression data generated using tiling arrays and predicted 139 and 517 polycistronic operons in Mycoplasma pneumoniae and Listeria monocytogenes, respectively. In addition, Oliver et al. also used continuous expressions over intergenic regions to detect 355 operons in L. monocytogenes based on non-strand-specific RNA-seq data [CITATION_3] .",
